of the Year in 2000.

00:10:47.955 --> 00:10:50.719
And he had a random mutation
that gave him six fingers

00:10:50.743 --> 00:10:52.971
on each hand,

00:10:52.995 --> 00:10:55.637
which turns out to be really useful
if you're a pitcher.

00:10:55.661 --> 00:10:57.301
(Laughter)

00:10:58.119 --> 00:10:59.849
How about non-random mutation?

00:11:00.415 --> 00:11:03.388
A non-random mutation is beer.

00:11:03.412 --> 00:11:05.110
It's wine. It's yogurt.

00:11:05.928 --> 00:11:08.264
How many times have you walked
through the forest

00:11:08.288 --> 00:11:09.851
and found all-natural cheese?

00:11:10.859 --> 00:11:12.102
Or all-natural yogurt?

00:11:13.046 --> 00:11:14.831
So we've been engineering this stuff.

00:11:14.855 --> 00:11:16.323
Now, the interesting thing is,

00:11:16.347 --> 00:11:17.965
we get to know the stuff better.

00:11:18.364 --> 00:11:22.077
We found one of the single most powerful
gene-editing instruments,

00:11:22.101 --> 00:11:23.888
CRISPR, inside yogurt.

00:11:25.028 --> 00:11:27.018
And as we start engineering cells,

00:11:27.042 --> 00:11:31.322
